      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A 30-year-old male with no history of prior immunization presents to the clinic with a clean, superficial wound incurred two hours prior while working in a garden. He has never received any doses of tetanus toxoid in his lifetime. What is the appropriate tetanus prophylaxis in this situation?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3103462",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 35113,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. A) Begin a full course of tetanus toxoid vaccination</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The management of tetanus prophylaxis depends on the wound type and the patient's immunization history. In this case, the patient has no history of prior immunization against tetanus, which places him at high risk of developing tetanus despite the wound being clean and superficial.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A full course of tetanus toxoid vaccination (3 doses) is indicated to provide both immediate and long-term immunity.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Tetanus immunoglobulin (TIG) is not required for clean wounds, even in patients with no prior vaccination, as the risk of infection is minimal in such cases.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The recommended schedule for tetanus toxoid in this scenario would include:</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The first dose at presentation.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The second dose 4 weeks after the first.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The third dose 6–12 months after the second dose.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. Administer a single dose of tetanus toxoid: </strong>A single dose of tetanus toxoid is insufficient for individuals who are completely unvaccinated, as three doses are required to induce adequate immunity.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. No intervention is required: </strong>This is incorrect because the patient has no prior immunization history. Tetanus prophylaxis is mandatory in such patients, even with a clean wound, to ensure immunity against tetanus.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D. Administer human tetanus immunoglobulin and a single dose of tetanus toxoid:</strong> TIG is only recommended for dirty or high-risk wounds in unvaccinated individuals. In this case, the wound is clean, so TIG is not necessary.&nbsp;</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Prevention of Tetanus in Wound</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/29/101.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"700\" height=\"234\"></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Where,</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A. Complete course of toxoid or booster dose in previous 5 years</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">B. Complete course of toxoid or booster dose in previous 5-10 years</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">C. Complete course of toxoid or booster dose in &gt;10 years ago</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">D. Has not had a complete course of toxoid or status is unknown.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ref</strong>: Apurba Sastry’s Essentials of Medical Microbiology 1/e p263, 2/e p273, Park 23/e p312, 24/e p330</span></p>",
