      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 47-year-old man with a history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease is hospitalized for an acute exacerbation and treated with broad-spectrum antibiotics. Ten days into his hospital stay, he develops watery diarrhea 3-4 times daily. There is no blood or mucus in the stool, and he has no fever. The stool odor is not foul-smelling. Which of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic test to confirm Clostridium difficile infection in this patient?</span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3549152",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 35114,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans.&nbsp;C) Stool polymerase chain reaction (PCR) for C. difficile toxin genes.&nbsp;</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>PCR testing </strong>for <strong>C. difficile toxin genes </strong>is <strong>highly sensitive </strong>and <strong>specific </strong>and is the <strong>preferred diagnostic test for C. difficile infection </strong>(CDI), especially in a patient with <strong>recent antibiotic exposure </strong>and <strong>symptoms consistent with CDI</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Immunofluorescence </strong>for <strong>C. difficile antigens </strong>is <strong>less commonly used </strong>due to <strong>lower sensitivity </strong>compared to PCR.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>ELISA for C. difficile toxins </strong>has been <strong>largely replaced by PCR </strong>due to <strong>lower sensitivity and specificity</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Stool culture </strong>for <strong>C. difficile is highly sensitive </strong>but <strong>less specific </strong>and <strong>takes longer</strong>, making it less ideal for initial diagnosis.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Clostridium difficile infection </strong>(CDI) in <strong>stool polymerase chain reaction </strong>(PCR) for <strong>C. difficile toxin genes </strong>. This method is <strong>highly sensitive </strong>and <strong>specific</strong>, making it the <strong>most suitable choice for diagnosing CDI</strong>, particularly in <strong>patients with recent antibiotic exposure </strong>and <strong>CDI symptoms. Immunofluorescence for C. difficile antigens&nbsp; </strong>is <strong>less commonly used </strong>due to its <strong>lower sensitivity</strong>. <strong>ELISA for C. difficile toxins </strong>is also <strong>less favored due to lower sensitivity </strong>and <strong>specificity</strong>. Stool culture for C. difficile&nbsp; is highly sensitive but less specific and time-consuming, making it less suitable for initial diagnosis.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref:&nbsp;</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Apurba Sastry&rsquo;s Essentials of Med Microbiology 1/e p266, 2/e p276</span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
